title: For Sale:  Yugoslavian SKS Project Gun
postcontent: I started this project when I was in gunsmithing school and never finished it. Since it's been sitting around for so long I doubt that I ever will, so here it is. I believe that all of the parts right down to the smallest pin and spring are accounted for, but this has been stored in my safe for quite some time, so I'm not 100% sure. I shortened the barrel to 16 1/8", crowned it and polished the exterior of the barrel. The stock that you see is a Fajen gunstock that I found some time ago that they used to make for the SKS. The Fajen handguard matches. You will have to remove the metal on the original handguard which is included to complete it. Also included is an aftermarket peep sight and a set of Wolfe springs in order to make the trigger much more tolerable. My intent when I started this was to make a really nice looking, highly polished and rust blued SKS. Yeah, I know, that's weird, but it sounded interesting at the time, and it still does, it's just not something that I'm going to finish.Taken pending receipt of funds.

Based on the Russian RPK light machine gun, the NHM features a stronger receiver and a longer, thicker-profile chrome-lined barrel measuring 20 inches (508mm) compared to the 590 mm (23.2 in) of the original RPK, along with a forward-mounted steel bipod. The NHM-91 was equipped from the factory with two 30-round magazines. Like the RPK, the NHM-91 utilizes a heavier-gauge stamped sheet metal receiver built from 1.5mm-thick stamped sheet metal instead of the 1mm thickness typical of a Soviet or European AKM. Other Chinese-made AKM rifles such as the MAK 90 and NHM 90 have thicker receivers as well, resulting in increased rigidity, heavier weight, and improved overall accuracy. Trigger pull weight is also lighter than other AK designs, and some users report the rifle capable of 2-2.5 minutes of angle accuracy or better with factory 7.62×39mm ammunition.

title: For Sale:  Weatherby Vanguard S2 .308 w/Talley Mounts
postcontent: I live in Tampa, but will be in Bokeelia April 25-27 and wanted to give it a shot while I was done there.  ****PLEASE NOTE the Nikon scope is not for sale.  Once the rifle is sold the scope will be going back to my buddy who loaned it to me****Purchased in October for my dad to share during rifle season.  Mission accomplished took a few hogs and a nice doe the last weekend with it.  Thought I might keep it, but he loves his AR15 and I have my own stable of stuff so going to let it go.  Maybe 50-60 rounds through it?  I have it covered in a soft camo non-adhesive wrap in the Mossy Oak Break Up Infinity flavor, but underneath is the grey synthetic Monte Carlo Griptonite stock with pistol grip and forend inserts, and right side palm swell (aids shooter comfort and control).  I will leave the wrap on, but of course if you are sure you want to buy it you are welcome to take it off and inspect the stock.  I think it looks great though and it's about $20 worth of wrap so it stays on for now.  The added bonus I found out after the fact was how quiet it makes the rifle.  We had a crazy acorn drop this year and when one would fall on my buddies rifle it was 'PING' so loud, but on mine it just sounded like an acorn falling on the ground.  Quiet is key.  You can also see a little bump on the comb and that is a home made cheek riser which I'd encourage you to try b/f taking off.  Most shooters don't even know how to shoulder a rifle properly into the cheek bone and since everyone has a different face a stock from the factory will fit only some people.  It might work for you and might not, but if you suffer from erratic accuracy a big component can be b/c of poor cheek weld.  If you only shoot paper for fun off a bench it's much less of a problem, but if you shoot offhand or odd positions at game it's critical.  24" barrel and while a lot of people talk about sub MOA this rifle off a bench indoors is a true MOA shooter *if* the shooter is capable of sub MOA shots. Meaning this rifle won't magically fix a bad trigger pull with the trigger finger hooked and yanking.  The .308 cartridge was designed to burn fully in 24" of barrel so we are getting the maximum muzzle velocity and range potential with any given ammo at 24".  I had this rifle zeroed at 200 so it was ~1.75 inches high at 100. With Hornady SST 165g I punched out several 3 shot groups of .75 to .8 MOA with calipers and never tested it again.  Adjustable 2 stage matech quality trigger adjustable from 6 down to 2 pounds(set at factory default of ~ 5)and a 3 position safety.  The 3 position safety was one of the reasons I bought this b/c dad is getting older and hey sometimes you forget things.  Forward position = fire.  Middle position = locks the sear only, but the bolt is free so you can unload with the safety on.  Rearward position = bolt and sear are locked.  The capacity is 5 + 1 and this rifle also has the hinged floor plate for ease of unloading the magazine. This is a fully enclosed bolt sleeve and fluted bolt.   The receiver machining is simply fantastic there is no wobble or slop it simply fits perfectly and is tight as a drum when closed.  If you have ever picked up say a Remington 700 made in recent years you will know what I'm talking about with loose rattling bolt/receiver play. While the scope is not included the Talley 1" scope mounts will go with the rifle.  They are machined for the Vanguard receiver and are an exact perfect fit, no lapping required just add your favorite 1" tube glass and you are good to go.  The rifle is absolutely perfect and was maintained by a neat freak.  Every time I shoot my rifle I run a bore snake through it even b/f I head home.  It's always been cleaned and lubricated with CLP and soft patches, plastic tool fittings only no metal.   ****PLEASE NOTE the Nikon scope is NOT for sale.****  Once the rifle is sold the scope will be going back to my buddy who loaned it to meCash only and for pick up only at my home in South Tampa.  No trades, but thanks for the thought.  I've done my best to be thorough here, but I know there will always be additional questions so please feel free to ask anything you like and I'll get back to you typically within an hour or so I live with my phone on my hip. Thanks for you time have a great day.
